A Day in the Life… 
The Intermediate Business Systems Analyst advances, configures, and integrates University enterprise systems using systems analysis design, implementation, development, software solution support skills, and understanding of business requirements. They configure, enhance, and streamline systems, provide data and analytic solutions, configure systems and business processes, and design and develop integrations into existing and third party systems to support the University’s strategic goals. The incumbent resolves complex problems and provides comprehensive recommendations and solutions.
As the Intermediate Business Systems Analyst, you will: 

In collaboration with business users, design and maintain systems solutions to meet the needs of the University and work with stakeholders to identify and understand their priorities;


Provide maintenance support for Finance and HR systems, identify problems, and work with other analysts and end users as necessary to resolve production problems;


Provide all system and project management documentation, as required;


Provide specifications for new configurations as well as enhancements and maintenance of existing systems, working through all work tickets as required, using tracking software to provide a maintenance record for all changes;


Test and provide quality assurance measures, working with Analysts, DBAs, developers, and stakeholders;


Serve as lead analyst/project leader for projects and enhancements of financial and HR systems, directing the work of other team members as required; Plan and schedule project deliverables, goals, and milestones;


Provide input into the design, planning, implementation, and governance of related systems;


Ensure adherence to policies, procedures, and standards, seeking input and advising others as necessary;


Plan for and successfully transition projects to operations for ongoing support.

What you need to Succeed… 

Completion of a related university degree;


A minimum of three years of experience with analysis, support, and leading of IT business processes, including configuring and implementing systems, leading projects, extracting and analyzing data using database tools (E.G. SQL), and designing and developing integrations;


Experience configuring ERP system (Especially Workday) is an asset;


Advanced understanding of Workday systems and information requirements, and business requirements;


Strong analysis, troubleshooting, and problem solving capabilities;


Knowledge of Service Oriented Architecture Concepts;


Strong understanding of, and ability to use, object oriented and database programming languages, including but not limited to, Java, XML, XSLT, EIB, SQL, VB.Net, ASP.Net, EDI, Web Services, or other integration technologies;


Knowledge of SharePoint and Microsoft Office solutions with advanced level of Excel knowledge;


Able to document systems and processes using a variety of methods and tools (e.g. UML (Unified Modeling Language), REA);


Ability to manage time and set priorities working with multiple users, tasks, projects and tight deadlines.

